00:01:33.220 --> 00:01:35.510
Now some of you
may be wondering,

00:01:35.510 --> 00:01:38.500
how can a person like myself,
a professional bodybuilder,

00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:42.370
grow up and never have a single
piece of meat in my life?

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:43.960
Well, to understand
that, you have

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:47.410
to understand a little bit more
about me and how I was raised.

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:50.290
So it all starts
back with my parents

00:01:50.290 --> 00:01:53.770
way down in South
America in Argentina.

00:01:53.770 --> 00:01:56.830
Whenever my parents were
both in their early 20s,

00:01:56.830 --> 00:02:01.780
they converted from Catholicism
to a new lifestyle of Hinduism.

00:02:01.780 --> 00:02:05.260
Now, they actually renounced
all material possessions

00:02:05.260 --> 00:02:07.570
and decided to live
a faith-based life

00:02:07.570 --> 00:02:10.060
and devoted themselves
completely to God.

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:12.460
And by doing this, they
followed their spiritual master,

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:16.675
their guru from temple to temple
from Buenos Aires, Argentina,

00:02:16.675 --> 00:02:22.840
to Florianopolis, Brazil,
to Miami, to New Orleans,

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:25.030
and eventually making a
home and settling in South

00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:27.860
Mississippi, where I was born.

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:30.940
Now, as you can
imagine, growing up

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:36.430
in a Hare Krishna farm in South
Mississippi was quite unique.

00:02:36.430 --> 00:02:41.890
We had a cow sanctuary,
where we accepted rescue cows

00:02:41.890 --> 00:02:45.100
from other farms that provided
milk for the community.

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:47.590
We also had a
self-sustaining garden,

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:50.440
which provided vegetables
and fruit for the community.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:54.040
There was also a temple,
where the surrounding members

00:02:54.040 --> 00:02:56.860
of the community would
practice Bhakti yoga, which

00:02:56.860 --> 00:03:00.010
is essentially devotional yoga.

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:01.960
And I would frequent
these temples,

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:05.920
and I would, as you can see,
dress in traditional Hindu

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:07.190
garments.

00:03:07.190 --> 00:03:08.110
We would wear tilak.

00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:09.610
We would wear neck beads.

00:03:09.610 --> 00:03:11.650
And growing up this way
was really quite unique

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:14.170
because I had quite a strong
connection with animals

00:03:14.170 --> 00:03:15.340
in particularly.

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:18.070
And I've learned certain
concepts growing up

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:20.740
this lifestyle that
I still follow today.

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:23.230
And one of those
concepts in Hinduism

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:25.400
is something called ahimsa.

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:28.300
Now ahimsa is an
ancient Sanskrit word

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:31.900
that roughly translates
into a meaning nonviolence.

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:36.430
So Hindus try to embody
this in every way

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:38.360
possible and in every
aspect of their life,

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:41.200
including the food that
they put on their plate.

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:43.510
So, essentially, it
means showing compassion

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:45.460
to all living beings,
including animals.

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:49.390
Because in order for an animal
to end up on your plate,

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:51.130
the animal had to
suffer and the animal

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:54.220
had to eventually die
for your convenience.

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:58.330
So if you can imagine,
I grew up in this bubble

00:03:58.330 --> 00:04:00.910
and then had to assimilate
outside of this bubble

00:04:00.910 --> 00:04:02.470
and go to public school.

00:04:02.470 --> 00:04:05.020
Now my parents were
very free thinkers.

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:07.360
They didn't really care much
about the outside world,

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:10.420
and they sent me to my first
day of kindergarten head

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:13.180
to toe dressed in
traditional Hindu garments,

00:04:13.180 --> 00:04:16.180
wearing neck beards,
wearing tilak on my forehand

00:04:16.180 --> 00:04:18.220
like I showed you in
the picture earlier.

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:20.470
And I quickly
realized how different

00:04:20.470 --> 00:04:22.340
I was from everybody else.

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:25.360
And not only did I quickly
realize, the kids in my class

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:27.640
quickly realized as well,
and they let me know.

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:31.270
So growing up in
South Mississippi

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:34.330
as a Hare Krishna was
very difficult at times

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:38.980
because I can remember bringing
my lunch and my lunchbox

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:41.740
to the class, and
opening up my lunchbox

00:04:41.740 --> 00:04:46.360
and immediately filling a room
with aromas of Indian cuisine

00:04:46.360 --> 00:04:49.180
because that's what I
was being fed at home,

00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:51.520
things like curry,
cumin, turmeric,

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:53.770
and all of these things
that are very aromatic.

00:04:53.770 --> 00:04:55.940
And kids would
immediately look at me,

00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:57.220
and they would look at the
food that I was eating.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:04:59.110
And they would begin to ask
questions like, what is that?

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:00.670
Why are you eating that food?

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:03.880
And as a young child,
it's very difficult

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:07.840
to explain a concept
like ahimsa to somebody

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:09.920
that's unfamiliar with it.

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:12.220
So what happened was
is that I constantly

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:17.320
had to defend myself and explain
my belief system growing up

00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:20.170
to kids that didn't
necessarily understand,

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:23.890
so much to the point where I got
almost self-conscious about who

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:27.040
I was as a person and ended
up becoming somewhat ashamed

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:29.830
of my background and how I
was raised because I was so

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:31.520
different than everybody else.

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:34.420
So when I would attend
parties, and birthday parties,

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:39.042
and different events at school,
and the parents of the kids

00:05:39.042 --> 00:05:41.500
would ask me why aren't I eating
the hamburgers or why am I

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:44.920
not eating the pizza, I would
simply just respond by saying,

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:47.380
I don't like it
because that was easier

00:05:47.380 --> 00:05:49.540
for me to say than
I don't eat it

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:53.170
because I don't believe in
harming other living beings.

00:05:53.170 --> 00:05:56.710
So, essentially,
I suppressed who

00:05:56.710 --> 00:05:58.900
I was as a person
and this mentality

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:02.952
followed me all the way up
until college, where I went on

00:06:02.952 --> 00:06:04.660
to study to get my
mechanical engineering

00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:05.830
degree in Louisiana.

00:06:05.830 --> 00:06:11.350
And what happened was after
I graduated from college

00:06:11.350 --> 00:06:13.870
in Louisiana, I had these
big dreams and aspirations

00:06:13.870 --> 00:06:17.560
of coming to California and
living the California lifestyle

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:21.740
and longboarding along the
beach in front of palm trees.

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:24.040
But what happened
was I ended up moving

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:27.144
to a place called
Bakersfield, which

00:06:27.144 --> 00:06:29.560
I don't know if many of you
are familiar with Bakersfield.

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:31.480
It's not too far from here,
it's only about 2 and 1/2 hours

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:32.350
north.

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:36.840
And Bakersfield is very similar
to Louisiana and Mississippi

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:39.960
in the sense that it is a
predominantly agriculturally

00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:44.970
based town with loads of
cattle farms, dairy farms.

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:48.120
They also grow lots of
crops in Bakersfield,

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:52.980
and I, in particularly, went
to work for an oil company

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:56.580
because oil is also heavily
prevalent in Bakersfield.

00:06:56.580 --> 00:06:59.070
So my job as a mechanical
engineer working for this oil

00:06:59.070 --> 00:07:02.370
company was to
essentially ensure

00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:04.890
that the pipelines, the
tanks, and the vessels

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:07.290
maintain their mechanical
integrity because whatever

00:07:07.290 --> 00:07:10.500
happens when you
extract these oils

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:12.750
and liquids from
the ground, they're

00:07:12.750 --> 00:07:15.450
highly corrosive to
metal in particular.

00:07:15.450 --> 00:07:18.270
So it was my job to
assess these assets

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:20.770
and make sure that they maintain
their mechanical integrity.

00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:24.649
Now while it was a very
intellectually stimulating job

00:07:24.649 --> 00:07:26.940
and a very important job
because I was not only keeping

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:31.140
the environment safe, I was
keeping the co-workers of mine

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:35.940
safe as well, it did not
fulfill me in any sort of way

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.850
because I was deeply
uninterested in what

00:07:38.850 --> 00:07:40.590
I was doing and going
to work every day,

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:41.760
working for a corporate job.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.590
And this actually made
me quite depressed

00:07:43.590 --> 00:07:46.410
because I had
achieved everything

00:07:46.410 --> 00:07:48.310
that I had ever wanted.

00:07:48.310 --> 00:07:49.200
I had made it.

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:50.880
I had graduated as an engineer.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.430
I had fulfilled
my parents dreams

00:07:53.430 --> 00:07:54.990
of giving me a
better opportunity

00:07:54.990 --> 00:07:57.810
to provide for myself and
my family financially.

00:07:57.810 --> 00:08:00.480
And this made me
very sad inside.

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:05.520
And what happened afterwards
is that I found an escape

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:06.990
through fitness.

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:09.270
So in Bakersfield,
there isn't much to do.

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:12.840
You either become very involved
with partying and drinking

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:14.790
or you find other more
productive outlets.

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:17.880
And I chose to spend my
time more productively,

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:20.250
working on myself and becoming
the healthiest version

00:08:20.250 --> 00:08:20.760
of myself.

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:24.690
Because what I had found
even looking at things

00:08:24.690 --> 00:08:27.240
as an engineer is that
everything can be broken down

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:28.650
into systems and processes.

00:08:28.650 --> 00:08:32.679
And your body, in particular, is
a very highly adaptive machine.

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:34.530
So if you can
understand the processes

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:37.080
and how your body works, you
can optimize it the same way

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:38.820
you can optimize
what type of fuel

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:41.520
you can put in a car to make
it operate better to prevent

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.929
maintenance from in the future.

00:08:43.929 --> 00:08:47.610
Now in that discovery what
I started looking into

00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:49.590
was the type of foods
that I was consuming.

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:52.197
And by this time, I was very
heavily focused in the gym.

00:08:52.197 --> 00:08:54.780
I was spending a lot of energy,
and I was seeing some results.

00:08:54.780 --> 00:08:57.870
And as a vegetarian
bodybuilder, I

00:08:57.870 --> 00:09:02.760
tended to follow a more
traditional bro science

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:06.330
approach to building muscle,
meaning that approximately 40%

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:08.700
of my calories were
coming from protein.

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:11.820
Now as a vegetarian, I
tended to really heavily rely

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:15.312
on things like whey
protein, cottage cheese,

00:09:15.312 --> 00:09:16.770
and certain types
of dairy products

00:09:16.770 --> 00:09:19.550
in order to meet my
protein requirements.

00:09:19.550 --> 00:09:24.170
Now along the same time, a
video that my mom happened

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:26.690
to share on Facebook
surfaced in my News Feed,

00:09:26.690 --> 00:09:28.530
and I looked into it.

00:09:28.530 --> 00:09:32.060
And it was showing what was
going on in the dairy industry

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:33.650
and at these dairy farms.

00:09:33.650 --> 00:09:35.930
Now I had always
grown up believing

00:09:35.930 --> 00:09:40.010
that it wasn't a real
issue drinking milk

00:09:40.010 --> 00:09:42.560
and consuming dairy
products because in my mind,

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:46.670
I justified it by the cows
weren't dying to provide milk

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:49.250
so there isn't really
anything wrong with it, right?

00:09:49.250 --> 00:09:50.960
But what this
video exposed to me

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:54.890
is the processes and the
systems that these companies

00:09:54.890 --> 00:10:01.840
use to extract milk
from their product.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:04.750
And I looked at it with
a different set of eyes

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:06.970
than I normally had
before because working

00:10:06.970 --> 00:10:10.210
in the corporate world taught
me how to look for efficiencies

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:13.360
and make the profit
margins for the company

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:15.420
that I worked with higher.

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:19.580
So in this video, they
show exactly what goes on

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:20.580
behind dairy industries.

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:25.950
And, yes, of course, there
are many, I would say,

00:10:25.950 --> 00:10:28.180
unethical practices that
go on in these industries.

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:29.638
But what really
caught my attention

00:10:29.638 --> 00:10:32.340
is the mechanical processes
that goes onto extracting

00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:33.750
the milk from these cows.

00:10:33.750 --> 00:10:36.480
And I immediately
related to it because it

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:38.820
looked very similar
to a processing plant

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:41.270
that I had worked in before.

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:45.470
So looking at this image with
a set of engineering lenses,

00:10:45.470 --> 00:10:48.940
I understood that there
was a guy that was exactly

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:52.480
like me that was working
for this company,

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:58.060
trying hard and thinking really
hard how to maximize efficiency

00:10:58.060 --> 00:11:02.080
from their systems and processes
at the expense of these living

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:05.470
beings and having no
regard for whether or not

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:07.930
they're suffering, whether
or not they're comfortable.

00:11:07.930 --> 00:11:10.120
So at that moment, I
made a conscious decision

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:11.740
that I wasn't
going to contribute

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:15.144
my dollar to supporting
these companies because by me

00:11:15.144 --> 00:11:16.810
supporting these
companies, essentially,

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:21.310
I was paying this guy's salary
to work harder and smarter

00:11:21.310 --> 00:11:23.050
and create more suffering.

00:11:23.050 --> 00:11:25.060
And this all goes back
to the word ahimsa,

00:11:25.060 --> 00:11:28.030
which basically means try to
live a most compassionate life

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:30.160
as possible.

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:34.170
After this, you could imagine
as a very enthusiastic

00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:37.000
bodybuilder, I
became very concerned

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.760
that I was giving up my
primary source of protein.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:50.710
And I Googled what are some of
the concerns or maybe health

00:11:50.710 --> 00:11:53.050
risks of giving up
dairy in particular?

00:11:53.050 --> 00:11:55.060
Because I've always
heard that dairy

00:11:55.060 --> 00:11:56.990
was a primary source of calcium.

00:11:56.990 --> 00:11:58.960
It was also a primary
source of protein or whey

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:00.850
protein in particular.

00:12:00.850 --> 00:12:03.630
And what I found is
quite astounding.

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:06.830
So, immediately, one of
the biggest statistics

00:12:06.830 --> 00:12:08.390
that jumped out
at me was the fact

00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:13.130
that studies show that 65%
of the world's population

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:15.422
is intolerant to dairy.

00:12:15.422 --> 00:12:17.380
That doesn't necessarily
mean they're allergic,

00:12:17.380 --> 00:12:19.480
but they show some
type of intolerance.

00:12:19.480 --> 00:12:21.640
Now this number
drastically increases

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:24.760
for people of Asian descent
and particularly people

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:26.610
of any kind of color descent.

00:12:26.610 --> 00:12:28.570
It goes up to the high 90s.

00:12:28.570 --> 00:12:32.890
Now these intolerances
don't show the same symptoms

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:35.620
as say an allergy in the
way that your body will

00:12:35.620 --> 00:12:38.170
go into some type
anaphylactic shock

00:12:38.170 --> 00:12:41.350
and produce antibodies
to fight these allergens.

00:12:41.350 --> 00:12:44.860
What happens is that these
symptoms are much more subtle.

00:12:44.860 --> 00:12:47.470
Essentially, you could be
suffering from an intolerance

00:12:47.470 --> 00:12:49.750
not knowing it and be
experiencing things

00:12:49.750 --> 00:12:52.780
like chronic fatigue,
chronic inflammation,

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:54.380
digestive problems.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:57.460
And I was experiencing every
single one of these things,

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.350
given the fact that I
was so predominantly

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:03.040
dependent on dairy
products for my protein.

